{"content":{"body":"If we are just defining the protocol and not the object that implements it, we could just not expect the callback called by the implementation to be called synchronously, right? Similarly to how for thenables we assume that the callback could be called asynchronously, but custom thenables can still call it synchronously","m.mentions":{},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773155775712,"senderName":"nicolo-ribaudo","senderId":"@nicolo-ribaudo:matrix.org","id":"$VpRAFu9bOcIln3jfnp6GfPyTFJvPiLG07zcVuqtdXOo"},
{"content":{"body":"bakkot: lol maybe \"task cancellation\"?","format":"org.matrix.custom.html","formatted_body":"<a href=\"https://matrix.to/#/@bakkot:matrix.org\">bakkot</a>: lol maybe \"task cancellation\"?","m.mentions":{"user_ids":["@bakkot:matrix.org"]},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773155840989,"senderName":"ljharb","senderId":"@ljharb:matrix.org","id":"$aUc0IT00Qs07xP1CIWA6u8Iywn3mYdEZGgMN2cEKx2M"},
{"content":{"body":"In the design I was envisioning, we'd be specifying it fully, but in principle we could leave it up to implementations I guess","m.mentions":{"user_ids":["@nicolo-ribaudo:matrix.org"]},"m.relates_to":{"m.in_reply_to":{"event_id":"$VpRAFu9bOcIln3jfnp6GfPyTFJvPiLG07zcVuqtdXOo"}},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773156057762,"senderName":"bakkot","senderId":"@bakkot:matrix.org","id":"$3--7dbY5m9ABumQWXai3ukW69uBpsdhNcOEoW_ApbAs"},
{"content":{"body":"but, given that all existing implementations do call it synchronously, I think that would end up being a de-facto requirement anyway, so it seems silly not to write it down","m.mentions":{},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773156082889,"senderName":"bakkot","senderId":"@bakkot:matrix.org","id":"$GDK7g44LBd2yxlJedVJ8EdEUTdvJXZm2iTQEhZt_pxM"},
{"content":{"body":"One reason is that promises have two possible \"done\" states while abort signals only have one","m.mentions":{},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773156449302,"senderName":"nicolo-ribaudo","senderId":"@nicolo-ribaudo:matrix.org","id":"$Awpbj0_vGraOYcF4ey6fJz8TuYHPrM06Uigc_mnGkb0"},
{"content":{"body":"So the only two that could even make sense are .any and .all, and not the rest","m.mentions":{},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773156536410,"senderName":"nicolo-ribaudo","senderId":"@nicolo-ribaudo:matrix.org","id":"$taXQqB1S4Q0nyEuydUs_f4IEC-wuIF6NQ9g_Kw_XFX4"},
{"content":{"body":"I could imagine .all being useful in some scenarios (e.g. a multiplayer system, where you want to cancel a request only when every requester cancels) but I also have never encountered one in real life","m.mentions":{},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773156591514,"senderName":"bakkot","senderId":"@bakkot:matrix.org","id":"$tuCuj8PSXK4kMysUL0zGgnD_3GgdeW5VCvKGnSt_m5Y"},
{"content":{"body":"abort signals have two states... possibly three: Pending and Aborted/Triggered are the two definite states... Never is potentially a third.","m.mentions":{"user_ids":["@nicolo-ribaudo:matrix.org"]},"m.relates_to":{"m.in_reply_to":{"event_id":"$Awpbj0_vGraOYcF4ey6fJz8TuYHPrM06Uigc_mnGkb0"}},"msgtype":"m.text"},"ts":1773159030943,"senderName":"James M Snell","senderId":"@jasnell:matrix.org","id":"$INXce4nuI3VPTSOg0IiYiSJOBL6YGYrD4RJDvVkh8hY"},
